intent: >
  Add CheckResult, the one-measurement-per-check data shape. Introduces
  the belongs_to-Site link and the (site_id, checked_at desc) index that
  slices 6 and 7 will read from.

slice: 2/8
kind: feature
behavior_change: additive

reversibility: entangled
# Adds a migration + new table + foreign key + index. Revert alone won't
# drop the table or the FK constraint.

scope:
  declared:
    - app/models/check_result.rb
    - db/migrate/*_create_check_results.rb
    - db/schema.rb
    - spec/models/check_result_spec.rb
  actual:
    - app/models/check_result.rb
    - db/migrate/20260412000212_create_check_results.rb
    - db/schema.rb
    - spec/models/check_result_spec.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/models/check_result_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop app/models/check_result.rb spec/models/check_result_spec.rb db/migrate/20260412000212_create_check_results.rb
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "status_code + error_message are both optional at the model layer. The mutual-exclusion business rule (exactly one of the two is populated) is HttpChecker's responsibility in slice 3, where the failure-mode taxonomy is actually designed."
  - "response_time_ms is required because even a failed fetch has a measured duration (time until the error was raised), and making it nullable would push the branching into every reader."
  - "No numericality / range validation on response_time_ms — the only caller will be HttpChecker and the DB enforces integer typing. Adding `numericality: { greater_than_or_equal_to: 0 }` at the model layer is YAGNI until there's a real pathway that could violate it."
  - "The compound index orders checked_at DESC because every intended reader (scheduler in slice 6, index view in slice 7) wants the most-recent row first. A plain ascending index would be cheaper to write but an extra sort on every read."
  - "has_many :check_results on Site is deliberately not added. belongs_to works without it, and the reverse side only becomes load-bearing when slice 6 or 7 actually queries site.check_results — adding it now is speculative generality."

deviations_from_plan: none

trade_offs: >
  Descending compound index vs ascending. Chose DESC to optimize the
  hot read path ("latest check for this site") at the cost of slightly
  more work on write. For an MVP that checks sites on a 30s+ cadence,
  writes are rare enough that this is a free choice; at high write
  volume the tradeoff would want revisiting.

self_review:
  error_paths: >
    Model-layer validation is permissive on oddball values (negative
    response_time_ms, future checked_at, status_code outside 100..599).
    Conscious punt: the only caller is HttpChecker, which will produce
    these values from actual HTTP exchanges. Enforcing "sane ranges" at
    the model layer is defensive programming against a caller that
    doesn't exist yet.
  performance: >
    (site_id, checked_at DESC) compound index chosen deliberately. Makes
    slice 6 ("site's last check") and slice 7 ("latest status per site
    in the index view") cheap index seeks instead of full scans or
    in-memory sorts. Worth calling out because every subsequent slice
    assumes this index exists.

confidence: high

reviewer_attention:
  - db/migrate/20260412000212_create_check_results.rb:13  # the DESC compound index
